observations.recommendation:
In order to present fairly and reliably the PPE accounts in the Statement of Financial Position, the Audit Team recommended that the City Mayor direct:
the Inventory Committee to conduct a thorough and agency-wide physical inventory of all PPE, avail of the advantages of the COA Circular
No. 2020-006 by complying its provisions, to ensure that property records are duly updated, reconciled with the accounting records, and that the resulting PPE balances are accurate and verifiable;
the Inventory Committee/CGSO to remove from the RPCPPE the items costing below ₱50,000.00 and treat them as semi-expendable items and include the same in the RPCSP;
the CGSO to reclassify/adjust and record the misclassified items to their correct account titles; and
the CAO to record the donated vehicles in the books.

We recommend that management:

require the City Engineer to include the Project Billboard in the Preparation of ABC and POW as one of the pay items;

require the BAC and the City Engineer to monitor the proper implementation of the billboard display at the project site to inform the public of the essential elements of the project.

We recommended that Management direct the City Accountant to:

facilitate the reconciliation of the city government’s recorded liability with that of the Provincial Government of Ilocos Sur (PGIS) receivable and record necessary adjustments;


make representation through the City Legal Officer with the PGIS to possibly have an agreement to remit the RPT and SET share and pay the loan amortization based on the records of the city government;

and initiate the reversion of payables to the barangays with no supporting records and no pending claims filed with the city government.

13.8.	We recommended that the City Mayor instruct:
the City Budget Office to prepare an ObR for the establishment of the PCF at the beginning of the year and also at the time of replenishment of the fund and not for every PCV;
the different offices to reimburse only non-recurring, emergency and petty expenses to the PCF. Petty Cash Fund should not be used for regular expenses, such as rentals, subscriptions, light and water;
event coordinators to properly plan and anticipate for the procurement processes of the budgetary requirements for every event that the agency will undertake to ensure compliance with the procurement law;
end-users or offices making the reimbursement to personally complete the documentary requirements for immediate processing and payment of the claim; and
the City Accounting Office to revisit the provisions of EO No. 77 for the prescribed rules and regulations of expenses and allowances for official local and foreign travels of government personnel and apply the correct rates on the per diems and other incidental expenses.

We recommended that Management:

require the City Accountant to coordinate with the City Assessor for the verification of the existence of land, buildings and other structures belonging to the city government and ensure that the same are to be included in their respective accounts in 
order to clear any doubts on the fair presentation of the PPE in the Financial Statements;

require the City Assessor to pursue titling or registration of all land/lots owned by the city government to assure the public that it has incontrovertible and absolute proof of ownership therewith, and to avoid any unnecessary claims from interested persons and anomalies consequential to non-registration;

direct the City Assessor to furnish the City Treasurer for her safekeeping copies of the tax declarations of the land, buildings and other structures owned by the city government to make sure that all documents that may prove ownership thereof are intact;

direct the Appraisal Committee led by the City Assessor with the primary objective of appraising properties to its fair market value to be adopted by the City Accountant as measurement in recognizing unrecorded properties with unknown acquisition cost or fair value in compliance with IPSASs 17;

direct the City Accountant to reconcile the accounting records with the actual land and other structures owned by the management to ascertain the validity and existence of such accounts. All noted differences as a result of comparison of both records (assessor and accounting) shall be cleared and resolved immediately; and

 require the City Accountant, City General Services Officer and the City Assessor to coordinate and obtain proof of donation or turnover of the Evacuation Center including complete descriptions of the structure to warrant its inclusion in the PPE and determine its actual cost.

We recommended that Management instruct the City Accountant to ascertain that all supporting documents in connection with any projects/equipment intended for donation/transfer include the following necessary attachments to warrant removal from the books:

SP Ordinance /Resolution approving the donation/transfer and authorizing the Local Chief Executive (LCE) to execute a Deed of Donation;


Deed of Donation or any legal document containing the elements of a valid donation of the projects signed by the donor/transferor and the done/transferee;


Journal Entry Voucher of the donee /transferee taking up the PPEs received; and


SB Resolution and/or Certificate of Acceptance /Acknowledgment Receipt on the acceptance of the donated/transferred project/equipment from the city government.

We recommended that Management:

through the initiative of the LCE, create an Inventory Committee composed of representative of the LCE, GSO, and accountable officer of the department or office concerned task to be responsible in the conduct of a thorough physical inventory taking of all PPE of the city government and after which shall reconcile the results of the count with the property and accounting records. The inventory listing of equipment shall be checked with the property card maintained by the City General Services Office as against the equipment ledger cards maintained by the Accounting Department and the total thereof shall be compared with those in the general ledger. The output of the Inventory Committee shall then be reported on the RPCPPE. This shall be submitted to the Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of each year; and

require the GSO to:

b.1.	maintain Property Cards for each class of PPE and are used to record the acquisition, description, custody, disposal and other information about the PPE;



b.2.	tag all equipment owned by the city government with the information of property description, property number, date of acquisition and the amount;


b.3.	remove from the list of PPE the items which were covered by a consummated IIRUP;


b.4.	prepare RPCI every end of each semester and submit to the concerned auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year; and

b.5.	prepare a summary of active or not yet cancelled ICS at the end of the year.

We recommended that Management ensure accounting of its properties by observing the procedures provided by existing rules and regulations in the custody and management of properties specifically:

Physical inventory of all the supplies and properties of the City Government be conducted by an Inventory Committee composed of representative of the LCE, CGSO, and accountable officer of the department or office concerned for check and balance; 

Maintain Supplies Ledger Cards per stock number, PPE Ledger Cards for each category of assets, and Real Property Ledger Cards for land by the City Accountant as well as Stock Cards per stock number and Property Cards per category of PPE by the General Services Officer;

Invite COA Auditor and a representative from the internal control unit who shall serve as witness on the physical inventory taking;

Require the Inventory Committee to prepare the RPCPPE and RPCI and reconcile the balances with the accounting and property records and submit to the Auditor within the prescribed period;

Determine the persons liable in order to pinpoint liability of unaccounted and/or lost properties; and

File a request for relief from accountability for lost items of PPE within the prescribed period in accordance with Sections 151 and 152 of COA Circular No. 92-386 dated October 20, 1992.

